<font color="#FF0000">SUICIDES-VIETNAM VETS</font><br>
<tt>Tue Jan 14 17:09:38 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To all concerned:<br>
     I have said in earlier messages, that the rate of suicides is less among Vietnam vets then among non-vets in the same age category.  As a writer, school teacher and historian on the Vietnam war, I will provide my source of data for that statement.  The Center for Disease control in Atlanta did what was called the CDC Vietnam Experience Study Mortality Assessment.  The study concluded that during the first 5 years after discharge from the service, deaths from suicide among Vietnam vets were 1.7 times more likely than non-Vietnam veterans.  After that intial postservice period, Vietnam veterans were no more likely to die from suicide than non-Vietnam veterans.  After the 5-years postservice period, the rate of suicides is less in the Vietnam veteran group than in the non-veteren group.  The mortality studies done bt the CDC and the Veterans Administration show that approximately 9,000 Vietnam vets have commited suicide.  These deaths were confirmed Vietnam vets.  Other claims of high suicide numbers are not as well researched or documented.  These figures were presented to the Hearing before the Committee on Veterans' Affairs-United States Senate, one hundredth Congress second session by Dr. Houk.  Thus, one has to accept the documented number over speculation and not as well researched studies.  As a historian and claims assistant for a Veterans of Foreign Wars unit, genuine vets are those, whose service in Vietnam can be proved by a copy of their DD-214 or discharge paper.  Also acceptable is a DD-215, which is a official correction to a discharge made by the VA or Personel Records Center in St. Louis.  I have seen many men claiming to be Nam vets, and suicide victims that were claimed as Nam vets, that didn't have proof they were Vietam.  These men had no listed <br>
service in Vietnam or no documents to verify service.  These numbers are sometimes counted by error as Vietnam suicide victims, which is totally wrong.  The CDC study counted only documentable vets, which makes their study documentable and acceptable.  I am in no way tring to dishonor the memory of those men that did take their own life.  They are as much casualties of the war as the 58,000 on the monument.  The false claims by many to be Nam vets or Vietnam suicide victims dishonors those that actually served and suffered in the war.  9,000 men may seem a low number and the possibility exists that some were missed in the count, but in the true study of the war and its effects, there is no room for speculation (that hurts everyone), only genuine documentable scientific study.
<p><code>--   (Joe) </code><p>


